 in Canadian foreign policy was over, suggesting a return to the priorities of gentler, more cooperative Liberal governments. But was the Harper era really so different? And if so, why? This comprehensive analysis of Canada’s foreign policy during the Harper years addresses these very questions. The chapters, written by leading scholars and analysts of Canadian politics, provide an excellent overview of foreign policy in a number of different policy areas. They also offer differing interpretations as to whether the transition from a minority to majority government in 2011 shaped the way that the Harper Conservatives conceived of, developed, and implemented international policy. The analysis is gripping and the findings surprising, particularly the contention that the government’s shift to majority status was far less important to foreign policy under Harper than it had been under previous governments. The reasons why reveal important insights into the Harper decade of foreign policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerthiaume, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoucher, Jean-Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarment, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapnick, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapnick, Adam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEnglish, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGattinger, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato